               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-204-person1729">
                  FRANCES 
                  TAYLOR
               <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1729" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1729" type="given" value="FRANCES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1729" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18281204-204-viclabel1088" type="occupation">widow</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281204-204-victim1728 t18281204-204-viclabel1088"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18281204-204-crimeloc1089">Henrietta-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18281204-204-crimeloc1089" type="placeName" value="Henrietta-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18281204-204-crimeloc1089" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281204-204-off1086 t18281204-204-crimeloc1089"></join>. I lost these articles on the 24th of November; I did not see them taken - I saw them about two hours before they were missed; the next day some persons gave me information; the prisoner frequently came to my shop to buy small articles.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-204-person1730">
                  MARGARET 
                  MAWN
               <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1730" type="surname" value="MAWN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1730" type="given" value="MARGARET"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1730" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Henrietta-court. The prisoner has been at my shop to buy some articles - one end of Mrs. Taylor's shop comes into the court; he came on the 24th of November and bought a penny article of me - and presently I saw him come by again with a pier table in his hand; he said he had made a purchase - I<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182812040094"></xptr>knew it had been Mrs. Taylor's - I do not know where the prisoner lived; he came by again in three quarters of an hour with another table which I also knew - and in about half an hour he came by with the third table; I am confident they were Mrs. Taylor's - I had seen them for about three weeks, and about half an hour before they were taken - I saw no oil-cloth or carpet.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-204-person1731">
                  HENRY 
                  HARRISON
               <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1731" type="surname" value="HARRISON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1731" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1731" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was informed the prisoner had stolen the tables, and when he came out of a shoemaker's shop, next door to Mrs. Taylor's, I secured him - this was on the evening of Friday the 28th; I accused him of taking the tables - he denied it; I took him into a room and accused him again; he said he wanted to speak to his nephew, but I would not let him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-204-person1732">
                  JAMES 
                  TOYE
               <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1732" type="surname" value="TOYE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1732" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1732" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a carpenter, and lodge with the prisoner at No. 3, George-street; he brought these three tables home one afternoon, and said he brought them from the Borough; I think it was on Monday week; I saw some carpet but no oil-cloth - I was at work when he brought them in, but I saw them in the evening; this was a quarter of a mile from Mrs. Taylor's.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-204-person1733">
                  THOMAS 
                  YOXALL
               <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1733" type="surname" value="YOXALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1733" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-person1733" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I took the prisoner, and asked him for the key of the door - he denied having it, but I found a small key which unlocked a box; I then went and took his nephew, (the last witness) to the office; the prisoner there produced the key of the door -I found these tables, and in the box I found this carpet and floor-cloth.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence I did not know, in my confusion, that I had the key; I bought the articles and paid for them.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18281204-204-verdict1090" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18281204-204-verdict1090" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 49.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18281204-204-punish1091" type="punishmentDescription">
